INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2,1,'2015-02-19 14:07:57','2015-02-19 14:07:57','Display ads that actually convert.Our ads have higher view rates as well as higer conversion rates.We don\'t enter bid wars','Advertisers Solutions','','publish','open','open','','advertisers','','','2015-03-10 20:01:28','2015-03-11 00:01:28','',0,'http://45.56.100.161:7000/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(4,1,'2015-03-13 17:50:48','2015-03-13 21:50:48','The world of online marketing is a fierce and competitive atmosphere, where you have to take full advantage of any available opportunities and maximize their potential benefits to see consistent, recognizable results. The Internet offers a wealth of multifaceted avenues for advertising in all different platforms, from video streaming for commercials to possibly connecting with thousands of people via social media sites. A long-term stalwart in internet marketing are banner ads. We’re all familiar with banner ads, there are tons of them everywhere, and there are just as many different resources for creating them. However, statistics show that banner advertising isn’t really as effective as many people perceive it to be, and conversion rates seem to be quite low in the grand scheme of things.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">When you’re looking at websites, chances are you’ve encountered pages that seem to just be cluttered with banner ads. In the earlier era of the Internet, banner ads were often flashing graphics with misleading text, frequently leading users onto a wild goose chase of random pages, spyware, and viruses. In general, banner advertisements began building a less than stellar reputation, and it wasn’t hard to see why. In previous decades, banners and other types of display advertising started to crop up all over sites, which many people found annoying or even damaging to their computers (if the banner was created by unscrupulous people like scammers and phishers). They sure draw attention, but not all of it is good, even if the business behind the advertisement is completely legit.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Too many pointless advertisements and phishing incidents involving display ads lead to the development of ad-blocking software and plugins for browsers. It has been said that less than 10% of Internet users are responsible for 85% of all of the clicks a display ad receives, and some of those aren’t even from real people, just bots. But if this type of advertising has garnered such negativity, and is so supposedly ineffective, why do people continue to use it in their online marketing campaigns?</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">First, let’s examine some statistics. A study analyzing ad campaigns from 18 different advertisers and over 250 million ad impressions tracked the conversion results from different strategies such as downloading programs and software, filling out questionnaires, and display and banner advertisements. Using the Pearson method of correlation, the study concluded that the correlation rate between a click and a conversion was staggeringly low---as low as 0.01. This was the lowest rate determined by the study, where a score of 0 would mean there was no correlation at all. That’s practically nothing!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The rates went up noticeably when relating to user interaction with display advertising. User interaction is a term that encompasses several things a website visitor might do, such as hovering over the ad with the mouse for more than one second, expanding the ad or maximizing the ad into full-screen, or clicking an exit link within the ad. When the users interacted or engaged with the ad, even just hovering over it, the correlation went raised significantly, to a rate of 0.49. While this still isn’t very high, it is a noticeable increase! A similar increase was apparent when analyzing the conversion rate in correlation pertaining to impressions, with gross impressions receiving a 0.17 rate between correlation and conversion, and viewable impressions having a correlation rate of 0.35.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">So perhaps, it is worth considering that display advertising and clicks isn’t the best way to gauge the success of your online marketing campaign. However, this doesn’t mean that display and banner advertising is entirely useless, although the way it typically utilized is often quite flawed. These statistics lend the interesting perspective that while people may not be interested in clicking ads or banners (no matter how legitimate they are), they certainly do notice them, and might find them intriguing. While metrics involving user engagement such as hovering and viewing are usually associated with campaigns focusing on brand recognition, this might be more useful for direct marketing than once thought.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Optimizing the view-ability and memorability of your display ads will draw more attention them, potentially enticing users to seek more information about your business or brand themselves. People like to feel in control of their Internet activities, which is one reason why many people distrust display ads and avoid clicking on them. Visual impressions may stand out far more, creating a recognizable image that will foster curiosity within the viewers. This may very well be a better way to measure the success of your marketing campaign. Display advertising isn’t entirely pointless, but to make the most of it, you need to approach it with a fresh perspective or a different angle.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">It has been said that the average person is exposed to at least 15,000 ads per month. But do you remember any of them? Do you tend to blow off advertisements and banners as just junk clogging up the stuff you’re trying to read? Or maybe, you won’t even see any ads at all, if you’re using an ad blocking program (some of which can even block video adverts). That doesn’t mean that display advertising is dead and useless, but it reflects that if you’re going to use it in your next marketing campaign, you might want to consider a different approach. Maximizing viewable impressions and magnetizing the power of mouse-over hovering might draw more attention than you think, and this can be a better way of measuring your overall reach rather than relying on the numbers from focusing data collection on clicks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"></p><img src=\"http://www.driventide.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/Conversion-Rate2.png\" alt=\"conversion rates\" />\r\n\r\n<i>image by driventide at their website {link to <a title=\"driventide\" href=\"http://www.driventide.com/2011/what-is-a-website-conversion-rate-and-why-is-it-useful/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.driventide.com/2011/what-is-a-website-conversion-rate-and-why-is-it-useful/</a>} </i>','Why Display Advertising Holds Such Low Conversion Rates','','publish','open','open','','low-conversion-rates-in-display','','','2015-04-24 10:39:31','2015-04-24 14:39:31','',0,'http://adomattic.com/?p=4',0,'post','',0),(5,1,'2015-02-21 18:21:11','2015-02-21 18:21:11','The world of online marketing is a fierce and competitive atmosphere, where you have to take full advantage of any available opportunities and maximize their potential benefits to see consistent, recognizable results. The Internet offers a wealth of multifaceted avenues for advertising in all different platforms, from video streaming for commercials to possibly connecting with thousands of people via social media sites. A long-term stalwart in internet marketing are banner ads. We’re all familiar with banner ads, there are tons of them everywhere, and there are just as many different resources for creating them. However, statistics show that banner advertising isn’t really as effective as many people perceive it to be, and conversion rates seem to be quite low in the grand scheme of things.\r\n\r\nWhen you’re looking at websites, chances are you’ve encountered pages that seem t