on is exposed to at least 15,000 ads per month. But do you remember any of them? Do you tend to blow off advertisements and banners as just junk clogging up the stuff you’re trying to read? Or maybe, you won’t even see any ads at all, if you’re using an ad blocking program (some of which can even block video adverts). That doesn’t mean that display advertising is dead and useless, but it reflects that if you’re going to use it in your next marketing campaign, you might want to consider a different approach. Maximizing viewable impressions and magnetizing the power of mouse-over hovering might draw more attention than you think, and this can be a better way of measuring your overall reach rather than relying on the numbers from focusing data collection on clicks.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"></p><img src=\"http://www.driventide.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/Conversion-Rate2.png\" alt=\"conversion rates\" />','Why Display Advertising Holds Such Low Conversion Rates','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2015-04-24 10:37:36','2015-04-24 14:37:36','',4,'http://adomattic.com/4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(445,2,'2015-04-24 10:39:31','2015-04-24 14:39:31','The world of online marketing is a fierce and competitive atmosphere, where you have to take full advantage of any available opportunities and maximize their potential benefits to see consistent, recognizable results. The Internet offers a wealth of multifaceted avenues for advertising in all different platforms, from video streaming for commercials to possibly connecting with thousands of people via social media sites. A long-term stalwart in internet marketing are banner ads. We’re all familiar with banner ads, there are tons of them everywhere, and there are just as many different resources for creating them. However, statistics show that banner advertising isn’t really as effective as many people perceive it to be, and conversion rates seem to be quite low in the grand scheme of things.